"de Souza Muñoz M.E., de Giovanni R., de Siqueira M.F., Sutton T., Brewer P., Pereira R.S., Canhos D.A.L., Canhos V.P.","openModeller: A generic approach to species' potential distribution modelling",2011,"GeoInformatica","15","1",,"111","135",,,10.1007/s10707-009-0090-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78751582399&partnerID=40&md5=68c1d4f7f6ac3800258a0dfcb1b2240e","Centro de Referência em Informação Ambiental, Campinas, SP, Brazil; PO Box 942, Lanseria, Gauteng 1748, South Africa; Malcolm and Carolyn Wiener Laboratory for Aegean and Near Eastern Dendrochronology, Cornell University, B-48 Goldwin Smith Hall, Ithaca, NY 14853-3201, United States","de Souza Muñoz, M.E., Centro de Referência em Informação Ambiental, Campinas, SP, Brazil; de Giovanni, R., Centro de Referência em Informação Ambiental, Campinas, SP, Brazil; de Siqueira, M.F., Centro de Referência em Informação Ambiental, Campinas, SP, Brazil; Sutton, T., PO Box 942, Lanseria, Gauteng 1748, South Africa; Brewer, P., Malcolm and Carolyn Wiener Laboratory for Aegean and Near Eastern Dendrochronology, Cornell University, B-48 Goldwin Smith Hall, Ithaca, NY 14853-3201, United States; Pereira, R.S., Centro de Referência em Informação Ambiental, Campinas, SP, Brazil; Canhos, D.A.L., Centro de Referência em Informação Ambiental, Campinas, SP, Brazil; Canhos, V.P., Centro de Referência em Informação Ambiental, Campinas, SP, Brazil","Species' potential distribution modelling is the process of building a representation of the fundamental ecological requirements for a species and extrapolating these requirements into a geographical region. The importance of being able to predict the distribution of species is currently highlighted by issues like global climate change, public health problems caused by disease vectors, anthropogenic impacts that can lead to massive species extinction, among other challenges. There are several computational approaches that can be used to generate potential distribution models, each achieving optimal results under different conditions. However, the existing software packages available for this purpose typically implement a single algorithm, and each software package presents a new learning curve to the user. Whenever new software is developed for species' potential distribution modelling, significant duplication of effort results because many feature requirements are shared between the different packages. Additionally, data preparation and comparison between algorithms becomes difficult when using separate software applications, since each application has different data input and output capabilities. This paper describes a generic approach for building a single computing framework capable of handling different data formats and multiple algorithms that can be used in potential distribution modelling. The ideas described in this paper have been implemented in a free and open source software package called openModeller. The main concepts of species' potential distribution modelling are also explained and an example use case illustrates potential distribution maps generated by the framework. © 2009 Springer Science+Business Media, LLC.","Ecological niche modelling; openModeller; Potential distribution modelling; Predicting species distribution","Anthropogenic impacts; Computational approach; Data format; Data input; Data preparation; Disease vectors; Ecological niche modelling; Ecological requirements; Free and open source softwares; Generic approach; Global climate changes; Learning curves; Multiple algorithms; openModeller; Optimal results; Potential distribution modelling; Potential distributions; Public health; Single computing; Software applications; Species distributions; Species extinction; Algorithms; Climate change; Data handling; Ecology; Forecasting; Packaging; Software packages; Open systems; ecological modeling; geographical distribution; geographical region; GIS; software; species occurrence",,,,,,"Peterson, A.T., Uses 